I have written to Rush Limbaugh the following:<br><br>
&quot;Rush, <br><br>
&quot;I have listened to you for years, agreed sometimes and disagreed at others.  But today's talk about Arlington National Cemetary without mention of today's events at Arlington is empty talk.  <br><br>
&quot;The real story is that the remains of three crewmembers who died during the Bat 21 mission on April 6, 1072 were interned at Arlington today.  You mention being  on the cutting edge of events, but it appears that when real heros who deserve recognition finally have their day, you and all the other news carriers can only talk about the political effects.  I too am unhappy about the selling of plots, if it happened, but that's not what I wanted to hear about Arlington today!  <br><br>
&quot;Why couldn't these true patriots have their day without a purely political event, manufactured by the news media, overshadowing our true heros.  The crew members, who were recovered during investigations and excavations which occured in 1989, 1992 and 1994, were buried at Arlington today.  There is not a word of this on any of the news.  The crew members were:<br><br>
Capt. Peter H. Chapman, Centerburg, Ohio<br>
1st Lt. John H. Call III, Potomac, Md.<br>
Tech, Sgt. Roy D. Prater, Tiffin, Ohio<br>
Tech. Sgt. William R. Pearson, Webster, N.H.<br>
Tech. Sgt. Allen J. Avery, Auburn, Mass.<br><br>
&quot;There was one airman and one Army aviator who's names were not released at the request of their families.  Tech. Sgt. William R. Pearson was buried in his home town last month.  Several of the crew who were not personally identified were buried in a group burial today.  My question to you is:<br><br>
&quot;Why, after all these years, cannot this nation give its real heros some due?  <br><br>
&quot;Why, Rush?<br><br>
&quot;If you want more information on the subject, check:<br><br>
http://www.pbs.org/cgi-bin/pov/response.cgi/discuss/203/<br><br>
